<p>World leaders at the G20 summit in Johannesburg adopted a leaders’ declaration at the start of the meeting, breaking with tradition, while the United States boycotted the event [dw.com#1][aljazeera.com#1][japantoday.com#1][abc.net.au#1][dawn.com#1]. South Africa said the text “can’t be renegotiated,” and officials said Washington pressured them not to adopt it in the US’s absence [straitstimes.com#1][dawn.com#1][dw.com#1]. The White House criticized the process as “shameful” and a spokeswoman said South Africa had “weaponised” its G20 presidency, while the declaration stresses the seriousness of climate change, praises ambitious renewable energy targets, notes heavy debt burdens for poorer countries, and affirms support for the Paris Agreement and free trade [dawn.com#1][michaelwest.com.au#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/FFDJMhem0Z0GkhXXVUXqrnJQ1apSTEiTH2g5b87qc4XPLSL3D8QTYwCmGyTG8FdZsbo6YOfz7T3iuyrUJgcLL7ItgfVNsAG-PSudvm5_' alt='G20 leaders, including Brazil’s Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva and host Cyril Ramaphosa, gather for a group photo in Johannesburg.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Leaders adopted the declaration at the start of the summit, breaking with the usual end-of-summit practice [dw.com#1][aljazeera.com#1][japantoday.com#1]</li><li>South Africa said the document “can’t be renegotiated” and was the product of a year’s work and an intense final week [straitstimes.com#1][dawn.com#1][michaelwest.com.au#1]</li><li>The United States boycotted the summit; a White House official called the process “shameful,” and a spokeswoman said South Africa had “weaponised” its presidency [abc.net.au#1][dawn.com#1][michaelwest.com.au#1]</li><li>The declaration highlights the seriousness of climate change, ambitious renewable energy goals, debt burdens in poorer countries, and support for the Paris Agreement and free trade [dawn.com#1][michaelwest.com.au#1]</li><li>Argentina did not endorse the declaration after quitting negotiations at the last minute but said it remains committed to G20 cooperation [michaelwest.com.au#1]</li></ul><blockquote>The declaration […] “can’t be renegotiated”. - Spokesperson for President Cyril Ramaphosa</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>South African presidency: Ramaphosa said there was “overwhelming consensus” for the declaration, and his spokesperson said it “can’t be renegotiated.” [dawn.com#1] (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1956785/g20-nations-adopt-declaration-without-us-input'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>White House: Called the process “shameful” and said South Africa had “weaponised” its G20 presidency by pushing the declaration over U.S. objections [michaelwest.com.au#1] (<a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/g20-summit-adopts-declaration-despite-us-boycott/'>Michael West Media</a>)</li><li>G20 host (South Africa): “We should not allow anything to diminish the value, the stature and the impact of the first African G20 presidency.” [dawn.com#1] (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1956785/g20-nations-adopt-declaration-without-us-input'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Argentina: Quit negotiations before the draft’s adoption by envoys and later said it could not endorse the declaration but remained committed to G20 cooperation [michaelwest.com.au#1] (<a href='https://michaelwest.com.au/g20-summit-adopts-declaration-despite-us-boycott/'>Michael West Media</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.dw.com/en/g20-adopts-declaration-despite-us-absence/a-74850499'>G20 adopts declaration despite US absence</a> - dw.com</li><li><a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/video/newsfeed/2025/11/22/g20-leaders-adopt-new-declaration-even-as-us-boycotts-summit'>G20 leaders adopt new declaration, even as US boycotts summit</a> - aljazeera.com</li><li><a href='https://www.abc.net.au/news/2025-11-23/g20-defies-trump-with-leaders-jointly-signing-statement/106041342'>Trump isolated at G20 with world leaders uniting behind joint declaration</a> - abc.net.au</li><li><a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1956785/